ysema","Distal acinar emphysema","Centriacinar emphysema"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe classification of emphysema is based on which portions of the acinus are affected. \u003Cstrong\u003EIrregular emphysema\u003C/strong\u003E has no specific pattern of acinar involvement. \u003Cstrong\u003EProximal acinar emphysema\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the respiratory bronchioles. \u003Cstrong\u003EPan-acinar emphysema\u003C/strong\u003E affects the entire acinus uniformly. \u003Cstrong\u003EDistal acinar emphysema\u003C/strong\u003E (also called paraseptal emphysema) specifically affects the alveolar ducts and sacs while sparing the respiratory bronchioles. \u003Cstrong\u003ECentriacinar emphysema\u003C/strong\u003E (also called centrilobular emphysema) predominantly affects the respiratory bronchioles in the central portion of the acinus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acinar emphysema is classified based on which anatomical regions of the acinus are affected","Distal acinar (paraseptal) emphysema affects the alveolar ducts and sacs while sparing the respiratory bronchioles"],"references":["Smith BM, Austin JH, Newell JD Jr, D\u0027Souza BM, Rozenshtein A, Hoffman EA, Ahmed F, Barr RG. Pulmonary emphysema subtypes on computed tomography: the MESA COPD study. Am J Med. 2014 Jan;127(1):94.e7-23. doi: 10.1016/j.amjmed.2013.09.020. Epub 2013 Oct 9. PMID: 24384106; PMCID: PMC3882898.","Angelini ED, Yang J, Balte PP, Hoffman EA, Manichaikul AW, Sun Y, Shen W, Austin JHM, Allen NB, Bleecker ER, Bowler R, Cho MH, Cooper CS, Couper D, Dransfield MT, Garcia CK, Han MK, Hansel NN, Hughes E, Jacobs DR, Kasela S, Kaufman JD, Kim JS, Lappalainen T, Lima J, Malinsky D, Martinez FJ, Oelsner EC, Ortega VE, Paine R, Post W, Pottinger TD, Prince MR, Rich SS, Silverman EK, Smith BM, Swift AJ, Watson KE, Woodruff PG, Laine AF, Barr RG. Pulmonary emphysema subtypes defined by unsupervised machine 